				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Pro=
babilistic classification algorithm</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Naive_corral.png" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/de/Na=
ive_corral.png/250px-Naive_corral.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"200" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"647" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"518"></a><figcaption>Example of a naive Bayes classifier depicted as=
 a Bayesian Network</figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statist=
ics">statistics</a>, <b>naive</b> (sometimes <b>simple</b> or <b>idiot's</b=
>) <b>Bayes classifiers</b> are a family of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Probabilistic_classification" title=3D"Probabilistic classificat=
ion">probabilistic classifiers</a>" which assumes that the features are con=
ditionally independent, given the target class.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-idiots_1=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Baye=
s_classifier#cite_note-idiots-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other words, a naive Bayes m=
odel assumes the information about the class provided by each variable is u=
nrelated to the information from the others, with no information shared bet=
ween the predictors. The highly unrealistic nature of this assumption, call=
ed the <b>naive independence assumption</b>, is what gives the classifier i=
ts name. These classifiers are some of the simplest <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_network" title=3D"Bayesian network">Bayesian net=
work</a> models.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-2"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Naive Bayes classifiers generally perform worse than more advanced m=
odels like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression" ti=
tle=3D"Logistic regression">logistic regressions</a>, especially at <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_quantification" title=3D"Unce=
rtainty quantification">quantifying uncertainty</a> (with naive Bayes model=
s often producing wildly overconfident probabilities). However, they are hi=
ghly scalable, requiring only one parameter for each feature or predictor i=
n a learning problem. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum-like=
lihood_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum-likelihood estima=
tion">Maximum-likelihood</a> training can be done by evaluating a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed-form_expression" title=3D"Closed-f=
orm expression">closed-form expression</a> (simply by counting observations=
 in each group),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-aima_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-aima-3">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 718">:=E2=80=
=8A718=E2=80=8A</span></sup> rather than the expensive <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterative_method" title=3D"Iterative method">iterative=
 approximation</a> algorithms required by most other models.
</p><p>Despite the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27=
_theorem" title=3D"Bayes' theorem">Bayes' theorem</a> in the classifier's d=
ecision rule, naive Bayes is not (necessarily) a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" title=3D"Bayesian probability">Bayesia=
n</a> method, and naive Bayes models can be fit to data using either <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_inference" title=3D"Bayesian in=
ference">Bayesian</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequenti=
st" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Frequentist">frequentist</a> methods.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-idiots_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-idiots-1"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-aima_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-aima-3"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Introduction">Introduction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaive_Bayes_=
classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Introd=
uction"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span=
></span></div>
<p>Naive Bayes is a simple technique for constructing classifiers: models t=
hat assign class labels to problem instances, represented as vectors of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feature_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Feature vector">feature</a> values, where the class labels are dr=
awn from some finite set. There is not a single <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> for training suc=
h classifiers, but a family of algorithms based on a common principle: all =
naive Bayes classifiers assume that the value of a particular feature is <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independence_(probability_theory)" t=
itle=3D"Independence (probability theory)">independent</a> of the value of =
any other feature, given the class variable. For example, a fruit may be co=
nsidered to be an apple if it is red, round, and about 10&nbsp;cm in diamet=
er.  A naive Bayes classifier considers each of these features to contribut=
e independently to the probability that this fruit is an apple, regardless =
of any possible <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_and_de=
pendence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Correlation and dependence">correl=
ations</a> between the color, roundness, and diameter features.
</p><p>In many practical applications, parameter estimation for naive Bayes=
 models uses the method of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum=
_likelihood" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Maximum likelihood">maximum lik=
elihood</a>; in other words, one can work with the naive Bayes model withou=
t accepting <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_probability" =
title=3D"Bayesian probability">Bayesian probability</a> or using any Bayesi=
an methods.
</p><p>Despite their naive design and apparently oversimplified assumptions=
, naive Bayes classifiers have worked quite well in many complex real-world=
 situations. In 2004, an analysis of the Bayesian classification problem sh=
owed that there are sound theoretical reasons for the apparently implausibl=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficacy" title=3D"Efficacy">eff=
icacy</a> of naive Bayes classifiers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_n=
ote-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> Still, a comprehensive comparison with other classificati=
on algorithms in 2006 showed that Bayes classification is outperformed by o=
ther approaches, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boosted_t=
rees" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boosted trees">boosted trees</a> or <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_forests" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Random forests">random forests</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classif=
ier#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>An advantage of naive Bayes is that it only requires a small amount =
of training data to estimate the parameters necessary for classification.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Probabilistic_model">Probab=
ilistic model</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DNaive_Bayes_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit =
section: Probabilistic model"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Abstractly, naive Bayes is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
nditional_probability" title=3D"Conditional probability">conditional probab=
ility</a> model: it assigns probabilities <span class=3D"mwe-math-element m=
