<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Discussion">Discussion</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaive_Bayes_clas=
sifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Discussion=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Despite the fact that the far-reaching independence assumptions are ofte=
n inaccurate, the naive Bayes classifier has several properties that make i=
t surprisingly useful in practice. In particular, the decoupling of the cla=
ss conditional feature distributions means that each distribution can be in=
dependently estimated as a one-dimensional distribution. This helps allevia=
te problems stemming from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curs=
e_of_dimensionality" title=3D"Curse of dimensionality">curse of dimensional=
ity</a>, such as the need for data sets that scale exponentially with the n=
umber of features. While naive Bayes often fails to produce a good estimate=
 for the correct class probabilities,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_=
note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> this may not be a requirement for many applications. F=
or example, the naive Bayes classifier will make the correct <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_a_posteriori_estimation" title=3D"Maximu=
m a posteriori estimation">MAP</a> decision rule classification so long as =
the correct class is predicted as more probable than any other class. This =
is true regardless of whether the probability estimate is slightly, or even=
 grossly inaccurate. In this manner, the overall classifier can be robust e=
nough to ignore serious deficiencies in its underlying naive probability mo=
del.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rish_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-rish-17"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Other reasons for the observed success of the naive Bayes classifier are d=
iscussed in the literature cited below.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relation_to_logistic_regres=
sion">Relation to logistic regression</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaive_Bayes_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Relation to logistic regression"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the case of discrete inputs (indicator or frequency features for disc=
rete events), naive Bayes classifiers form a <i>generative-discriminative</=
i> pair with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multinomial_logistic_=
regression" title=3D"Multinomial logistic regression">multinomial logistic =
regression</a> classifiers: each naive Bayes classifier can be considered a=
 way of fitting a probability model that optimizes the joint likelihood <sp=
