<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spam_filtering">Spam filter=
ing</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaive_Ba=
yes_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: S=
pam filtering"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Naive Bayes classifiers are a popular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistical</a> technique of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-mail_filtering" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"E-mail filtering">e-mail filtering</a>. They typically use <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bag-of-words_model" title=3D"Bag-of-words=
 model">bag-of-words</a> features to identify <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Email_spam" title=3D"Email spam">email spam</a>, an approach co=
mmonly used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Document_classifica=
tion" title=3D"Document classification">text classification</a>. Naive Baye=
s classifiers work by correlating the use of tokens (typically words, or so=
metimes other things), with spam and non-spam e-mails and then using <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayes%27_theorem" title=3D"Bayes' theore=
m">Bayes' theorem</a> to calculate a probability that an email is or is not=
 spam.
</p><p><b>Naive Bayes spam filtering</b> is a baseline technique for dealin=
g with spam that can tailor itself to the email needs of individual users a=
nd give low <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/False_positive" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"False positive">false positive</a> spam detection=
 rates that are generally acceptable to users. Bayesian algorithms were use=
d for email filtering as early as 1996.  Although naive Bayesian filters di=
d not become popular until later, multiple programs were released in 1998 t=
o address the growing problem of unwanted email.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_class=
ifier#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>  The first scholarly publication on Bayesia=
n spam filtering was by Sahami et al. in 1998.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classif=
ier#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Variants of the basic technique have been implemented in a number of=
 research works and commercial <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Com=
puter_software" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Computer software">software<=
/a> products.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Man=
y modern mail <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Client_(computing)" =
title=3D"Client (computing)">clients</a> implement Bayesian spam filtering.=
 Users can also install separate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
-mail_filtering" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"E-mail filtering">email fil=
tering programs</a>. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Server-side" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Server-side">Server-side</a> email filters, =
such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDSPAM&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"DSPAM (page does not e=
xist)">DSPAM</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rspamd" title=3D=
"Rspamd">Rspamd</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-22"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpamAssassin" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"SpamAssassin">SpamAssassin</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-twsSep14y=
y_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_=
Bayes_classifier#cite_note-twsSep14yy-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/SpamBayes" title=3D"SpamBayes">SpamBayes</a>,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-twsSep2_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-twsSep2-24"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bogofilter" title=3D"Bogofilter">Bogofilt=
er</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-Spam_SMTP_Proxy" =
title=3D"Anti-Spam SMTP Proxy">ASSP</a>, make use of Bayesian spam filterin=
g techniques, and the functionality is sometimes embedded within <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mail_server" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Mail server">mail server</a> software itself. <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/CRM114_(program)" title=3D"CRM114 (program)">CRM114</a>, oft ci=
ted as a Bayesian filter, is not intended to use a Bayes filter in producti=
on, but includes the =E2=80=B3unigram=E2=80=B3 feature for reference.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Dealing_with_rare_words">De=
aling with rare words</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DNaive_Bayes_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=
=3D"Edit section: Dealing with rare words"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In the case a word has never been met during the learning phase, both th=
e numerator and the denominator are equal to zero, both in the general form=
ula and in the spamicity formula. The software can decide to discard such w=
ords for which there is no information available.
</p><p>More generally, the words that were encountered only a few times dur=
ing the learning phase cause a problem, because it would be an error to tru=
st blindly the information they provide. A simple solution is to simply avo=
id taking such unreliable words into account as well.
</p><p>Applying again Bayes' theorem, and assuming the classification betwe=
en spam and ham of the emails containing a given word ("replica") is a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random varia=
ble">random variable</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta=
_distribution" title=3D"Beta distribution">beta distribution</a>, some prog=
rams decide to use a corrected probability:
</p>
