<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Other_heuristics">Other heu=
ristics</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaiv=
e_Bayes_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Other heuristics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>"Neutral" words like "the", "a", "some", or "is" (in English), or their =
equivalents in other languages, can be ignored. These are also known as <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stop_words" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Stop words">Stop words</a>. More generally, some bayesian filtering f=
ilters simply ignore all the words which have a spamicity next to 0.5, as t=
hey contribute little to a good decision. The words taken into consideratio=
n are those whose spamicity is next to 0.0 (distinctive signs of legitimate=
 messages), or next to 1.0 (distinctive signs of spam). A method can be for=
 example to keep only those ten words, in the examined message, which have =
the greatest <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absolute_value" title=
=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a>&nbsp;|0.5&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;<i>pI<=
/i>|.
</p><p>Some software products take into account the fact that a given word =
appears several times in the examined message,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classif=
ier#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> others don't.
</p><p>Some software products use <i>patterns</i> (sequences of words) inst=
ead of isolated natural languages words.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#ci=
te_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> For example, with a "context window" of four words,=
 they compute the spamicity of "Viagra is good for", instead of computing t=
he spamicities of "Viagra", "is", "good", and "for". This method gives more=
 sensitivity to context and eliminates the Bayesian noise better, at the ex=
pense of a bigger database.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Disadvantages">Disadvantage=
s</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DNaive_Baye=
s_classifier&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Dis=
advantages"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Depending on the implementation, Bayesian spam filtering may be suscepti=
ble to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_poisoning" title=
=3D"Bayesian poisoning">Bayesian poisoning</a>, a technique used by spammer=
s in an attempt to degrade the effectiveness of spam filters that rely on B=
ayesian filtering. A spammer practicing Bayesian poisoning will send out em=
ails with large amounts of legitimate text (gathered from legitimate news o=
r literary sources). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E-mail_spam" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"E-mail spam">Spammer</a> tactics include ins=
ertion of random innocuous words that are not normally associated with spam=
, thereby decreasing the email's spam score, making it more likely to slip =
past a Bayesian spam filter. However, with (for example) <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Graham_(programmer)" title=3D"Paul Graham (prog=
rammer)">Paul Graham</a>'s scheme only the most significant probabilities a=
re used, so that padding the text out with non-spam-related words does not =
affect the detection probability significantly.
</p><p>Words that normally appear in large quantities in spam may also be t=
ransformed by spammers. For example, =C2=ABViagra=C2=BB would be replaced w=
ith =C2=ABViaagra=C2=BB or =C2=ABV!agra=C2=BB in the spam message. The reci=
pient of the message can still read the changed words, but each of these wo=
rds is met more rarely by the Bayesian filter, which hinders its learning p=
rocess. As a general rule, this spamming technique does not work very well,=
 because the derived words end up recognized by the filter just like the no=
rmal ones.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Another technique used to try to defeat Bayesian spam filters is to =
replace text with pictures, either directly included or linked. The whole t=
ext of the message, or some part of it, is replaced with a picture where th=
e same text is "drawn". The spam filter is usually unable to analyze this p=
icture, which would contain the sensitive words like =C2=ABViagra=C2=BB. Ho=
wever, since many mail clients disable the display of linked pictures for s=
ecurity reasons, the spammer sending links to distant pictures might reach =
fewer targets. Also, a picture's size in bytes is bigger than the equivalen=
t text's size, so the spammer needs more bandwidth to send messages directl=
y including pictures. Some filters are more inclined to decide that a messa=
ge is spam if it has mostly graphical contents. A solution used by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google" title=3D"Google">Google</a> in it=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gmail" title=3D"Gmail">Gmail</a>=
 email system is to perform an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opt=
ical_character_recognition" title=3D"Optical character recognition">OCR (Op=
tical Character Recognition)</a> on every mid to large size image, analyzin=
g the text inside.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-30"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Naive_Bayes_classifier#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
